%[text] # Craig's robotics book and learning from Robotics toolbox interactive script
%[text] 2025 Oct 27 MatLab practice from chap 1 to 4
%[text] ## Chap 2 Mapping and  other transforms
%%
%[text] ### 2.1 Rotation with 3D co-ordinate, based on an axis (z) using directional cosine projection
%[text] 1. $^A\_B R = \\left\[\n\\matrix{\\hat{x}\_B \\cdot \\hat{x}\_A & \\hat{y}\_B \\cdot \\hat{x}\_A & \\hat{z}\_B \\cdot \\hat{x}\_A \\cr \n\\hat{x}\_B \\cdot \\hat{y}\_A & \\hat{y}\_B \\cdot \\hat{y}\_A & \\hat{z}\_B \\cdot \\hat{y}\_A \\cr\n\\hat{x}\_B \\cdot \\hat{z}\_A & \\hat{y}\_B \\cdot \\hat{z}\_A & \\hat{z}\_B \\cdot \\hat{z}\_A }\n\\right\]\n=\\left\[\n\\matrix{^{A}\\hat{x}\_B & ^{A}\\hat{y}\_B & ^{A}\\hat{z}\_B}\n\\right\]\n=\\left\[\n\\matrix{^{B}\\hat{x}\_A^T & ^{B}\\hat{y}\_A^T & ^{B}\\hat{z}\_A^T}\n\\right\]$
%[text] 2. $^{A}\_BR = ^{B}\_AR^T = ^{B}\_AR^{-1}$
%[text] 3.  $^{A}p\_x = ^{B}\\hat{x}\_A \\cdot ^{B}p$, $^{A}p\_y = ^{B}\\hat{y}\_A \\cdot ^{B}p$, $^{A}p\_z = ^{B}\\hat{z}\_A \\cdot ^{B}p$ \
%[text] #### Example 2.1:
%[text] 3D Euler frame A: $\\{A\\} = \\left\[\n\\matrix{ \\hat{x}\_A & \\hat{y}\_A & \\hat{z}\_A}\n\\right\]$, $\\hat{x}\_A = \\left\[ \\matrix{1 & 0 & 0} \\right\]^T$ and $\\hat{y}\_A = \\left\[ \\matrix{0 & 1 & 0} \\right\]^T$, and $\\hat{z}\_A = \\left\[ \\matrix{0 & 0 & 1} \\right\]^T$.
%[text] 3D Euler fram B: rotate about axis Z, where $\\hat{z}\_A = \\hat{z}\_B$, counter clock wise for $\\theta = 30^o$
%[text] ![](text:image:1da6)
%[text] $^A\_BR = \\left \[\n\\matrix{\\cos{30} & -\\sin{30} & 0 \\cr \\sin{30} & \\cos{30} &0 \\cr 0 & 0  & 1}\n\\right\]$, thus $\\{B\\} = \\left\[ \\matrix{\n\\sqrt{3}/2 & -1/2 & 0 \\cr \n1/2 & \\sqrt{3}/2 & 0 \\cr \n0 & 0 & 1\n}\\right\]$, as $\\hat{x}\_B = \\left\[ \\matrix{ \n\\sqrt{3}/2 \\cr\n1/2 \\cr\n0\n}\\right\]$, specifically it is $^A\\hat{x}\_B$. $\\hat{y}\_B = \\left\[ \\matrix{ \n-1/2 \\cr\n\\sqrt{3}/2 \\cr\n0\n}\\right\]$
%[text] Note that the first, second and third row is $^B\\hat{x}\_A ^T= \\left\[\\matrix{\n\\sqrt{3}/2 & -1/2 &0\n}\\right\] $, $^B\\hat{y}\_A ^T= \\left\[\\matrix{\n1/2 & \\sqrt{3}/2 & 0\n}\\right\] $, and $^B\\hat{z}\_A ^T= \\left\[\\matrix{\n0 & 0 & 1\n}\\right\] $
%[text] ![](text:image:9cea)
%[text] If we have a point p that is fixed in space, but only rotate the frame from frame:$\\{A\\}$ to frame: $\\{B\\}$, given $^{B}p = \\left\[ \\matrix{\n0 \\cr \n2 \\cr\n0\n}\\right\]$ assigned with this vector on against frame B. then for 
%[text] $^{A}p = \\left\[ \\matrix{\np\_x \\cr\np\_y \\cr\np\_z\n}\\right\] = \n \\left\[ \\matrix{\n-1 \\cr\n\\sqrt{3} \\cr\n0\n}\\right\]=\n\\left\[ \\matrix{\n\\cos{30} & -\\sin{30} & 0 \\cr\n\\sin{30} & \\cos{30} & 0 \\cr\n0 & 0 & 1\n}\\right\]\n\\left\[\\matrix{\n0 \\cr\n2 \\cr\n0\n}\\right\]$
% code example of using a rotational matrix from euler angles: eul
% eul2rotm([1/3*pi/2 0 0])   % remember in MatLab, euler is z-y-x!!!
% The above example of calculating:
p_frameB = [0 2 0]'     % point vector (translation vector) only in three numerals, not distinquishable %[output:50123f89]
p_frameA = eul2rotm([1/3*pi/2 0 0])*p_frameB    % practicing call direct use of eul2rotm (euler angle to rotational matrix) function %[output:9848a527]
%[text] If we have a fixed point in space, and need just the translation... it is done directly by
p_frameA = [0 2 0]' + [3 1 0]' %[output:5c1087aa]

clear p*    % the above is example 2.1 on page 26 in Craig's book.
%[text] ![](text:image:6ab7)
% using transformation operator to find directly the ^Ap presented if given
% ^Bp as like the example 2.2 on page 29
p_frameB = [3 7 0]';
p_Borg = [10 5 0]';   % frameB origin
frameB_orientation = se3([30/180*pi 0 0],'eul').rotm();
T_ab = se3(frameB_orientation,p_Borg')  %[output:2e6e7962]
p_frameA = T_ab.tform*([p_frameB' 1]');
p_frameA = p_frameA(1:3) %[output:606ed8d2]

clear all
%%
%[text] ### 2.2 Translation with rotation becomes transformation
%[text] using standard vector addition: $^A p = ^ B p + ^A p\_{BORG}$, as BORG= B's orgin
%[text] ![](text:image:3b86)
%[text] Since $^B p = ^A \_B R ^B p$, then $^A p = ^A \_B R ^B p + ^A p\_{BORG}$ can be made into a general mapping from one frame making it:
%[text] $\\left\[ \\matrix{\n^A p \\cr\n1\n}\\right\] = \\left\[\\matrix{\n^A \_B R & ^A p\_{BORG} \\cr\n0,0,0 & 1\n}\\right\] = \\left\[\\matrix{\n^B p \\cr\n1\n}\\right\]$
%[text] If using Euler-angle presentation $(\\hat{x} -\\hat{y}-\\hat{z}, \\alpha-\\beta-\\gamma)$
%[text] $R\_x \\left(\\alpha \\right)=\\left\\lbrack \\begin{array}{ccc}\n1 & 0 & 0\\\\\n0 & \\cos \\alpha  & -\\sin \\alpha \\\\\n0 & \\sin \\alpha  & \\cos \\alpha \n\\end{array}\\right\\rbrack${"editStyle":"visual"} $R\_y \\left(\\beta \\right)=\\left\\lbrack \\begin{array}{ccc}\n\\cos \\beta  & 0 & \\sin \\beta \\\\\n0 & 1 & 0\\\\\n-\\sin \\beta  & 0 & \\cos \\beta \n\\end{array}\\right\\rbrack${"editStyle":"visual"} $R\_z \\left(\\gamma \\right)=\\left\\lbrack \\begin{array}{ccc}\n\\cos \\gamma  & -\\sin \\gamma  & 0\\\\\n\\sin \\gamma  & \\cos \\gamma  & 0\\\\\n0 & 0 & 1\n\\end{array}\\right\\rbrack${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] can be used to combine into a local orentation R matrix.
%[text] Also, by convention, it is normal to put only one zero under the $^A\_BR$ 3 by 3 matrix.
%[text] #### Example 2.2: ploting and exercise using the most of robotics toolbox with pre-defined object
% example for defining a new frame and plot using the plotframe.m function

disp('Using universal frame as {A}, please input new frame origin: (x, y, z)') %[output:7c1cbc47]
% newFrameOrigin = input('Enter the new frame origin as a vector [x, y, z]'': ');
newFrameOrigin = [3 14 0] %[output:202a6156]
% Define the directional cosines for the transformation
% dirCos = eye(3); % Identity matrix as an example for no rotation

disp('Needs new frame {B} orientation, try to make it orthnormal, or can rotate it by providing random ZYX axis order which is also denoted as "Roll Pitch Yaw (rpy)."') %[output:6fa9f79a]
% disp('https://www.mathworks.com/help/robotics/ug/coordinate-transformations-in-robotics.html')

%[text] The following the code is from "plotframe" downloaded from MatLab center 
figure %[output:61bf263d]
axes( 'DataAspectRatio', [1 1 1], 'View', [37.5 30] ) %[output:61bf263d]
plotframe( 'LabelBasis', true, ... %[output:61bf263d]
    'Labels', {'X_{world}','Y_{world}','Z_{world}'}, ... %[output:61bf263d]
    'TextProperties', {'FontAngle','italic'} ) %[output:61bf263d]
xlabel( 'X' ), ylabel( 'Y' ), zlabel( 'Z' ) %[output:61bf263d]
axis padded %[output:61bf263d]
%[text] Using robotics toolbox object SE2, SE3 or other euler angles for tranformation:
% se3 for orientation with position in 3D (declare a frame f1, f2... etc)
% so3 for orientation only, remember orientation is with 3 by 3 matrix
% (decalre a orentation, o1, o2... etc, this time using Euler angles)
% against 3D normal world frame.

% position is either p1, p2... etc [0 3 1] or [0;3;1] etc
% euler angles either eul1, eul2, associated at p1, p2 points

eul1 = [0 0 0];  % euler angle in z-y-x rotation sequence, roll-pitch-yaw
eul2 = 2*pi*rand(1,3);  % second rotation

p1 = newFrameOrigin;
p2 = [3 14 5];

f1 = se3(eul1,"eul",p1)      % f1 frame object created by orientation eul1 and point p1  %[output:32f24d99]
f2 = se3(eul2,"eul",p2) %[output:5fabb50e]
%[text] plot the same figure so to show the new frames "f1", and "f2" at locations "p1" and "p2".
figure %[output:629ab200]
hold on %[output:629ab200]
%axes( 'DataAspectRatio', [1 1 1], 'View', [37.5 30] )
%rot = rotm(f1)           % rotm = extract rotational matrix from object "r" 
%plotframe('LabelBasis', true)   % using plotframe to have standard basis (feels like having eul0, p0, f0)
plotTransforms(f1)      % one can use plotTransform to plot 3D may be "un-rationed" %[output:629ab200]

plotTransforms(f2) %[output:629ab200]
plotline(p1,p2) %[output:629ab200]
plotline([0 0 0],p1)    % calling personal function plotline.m (later) so to use similar way like plotframe.m %[output:629ab200]
hold off %[output:629ab200]
%[text] All the above scripts are using the most of Robotics toolbox, as using its opject to make a frame objects, and then using rotm(SE3) to extract rotation matrix, using trvec(SE3)  to extract tranlation matrix, and tform(SE3) to extract homogeneous tranformation. One more concept also uses quaternion $(a+b\\hat{i}+c\\hat{j}+d\\hat{k})$, which is also a shorthand notation to present a full orientation for a "frame". It still needs a "position".
% remember: rotm = rotational_Matrix, trvec = translation_vector.
% it is a function from tranformation.rotm, and many others inside the se3
% object, that can be checked with "help se3"

% in Aerospace toolbox, there is a randrot(m) function, that can be used to
% make a randomized quaternion, or we can make random number angles in 2pi
% and random positions in 3D.
p = [zeros(3,1) round(10*rand(3,2))]    % location points vector {p} 3 by n, now in translation vector rows... %[output:34b6e0b8]
q =[quaternion(0,0,0,0) randrot(1,2)];  % making quaternion objects {q} 1 by n matrix indexed, now in quaternion...
e = quat2rotm(q);                       % transforming the above {q} into numerical rotational matrices 3 by 3 by n-1
e(:,:,1) = eye(3)                       % re-assureing the first rotational matrix is eye(3) so to represent x-y-z %[output:30a73ba8]

figure %[output:4210dcb8]
axes( 'DataAspectRatio', [1 1 1], 'View', [37.5 30] ) %[output:4210dcb8]
plotframe(e(:,:,1),p(:,1)) %[output:4210dcb8]
xlabel( 'X' ), ylabel( 'Y' ), zlabel( 'Z' ) %[output:4210dcb8]
axis padded %[output:4210dcb8]
hold on %[output:4210dcb8]
plotframe(e(:,:,2),p(:,2)) %[output:4210dcb8]
plotframe(e(:,:,3),p(:,3)) %[output:4210dcb8]
%fr = se3()
plotline([0 0 0],p(:,2)') %[output:4210dcb8]
plotline(p(:,2)',p(:,3)') %[output:4210dcb8]
plotline([0 0 0],p(:,3)') %[output:4210dcb8]

clear e*
clear f*
clear newFrameOrigin
clear p*
clear q
%%
%[text] ### 2.3 Transformation operator as se3 object and manipulation
%[text] using standard vector addition: $^A p = ^ B p + ^A p\_{BORG}$, as BORG= B's orgin
%[text] ![](text:image:32b3)
%[text] Full homogeneous transform (rotation + translation) is "Transfomed" using the operation(s): ($ ^A\_B T$). Note that the most important operation is that it can combine multiple frame relations: $^A\_C T = ^A\_B T ^B\_C T $.
%[text] the operation is using the Fig. 2.12, where $^Bp = ^B \_C T ^C p$, as $^B \_C T = \\left\[ \\matrix{\n^B \_C R & ^BP\_{CORG} \\cr\n0 & 1\n}\\right\]$, showing that $^B p = ^B\_C R ^Cp + ^Bp\_{CORG} $, then using the same idea, as $^A\_BT = \\left\[\\matrix{\n^A\_BR & ^Ap\_{BORG} \\cr\n0 & 1\n}\\right\]$, thus it is true that:
%[text] $^A\_CT= \n\\left\[\\matrix{\n^A\_BR^B\_CR & ^B\_AR^Bp\_{CORG}+^Ap\_{BORG} \\cr\n0 & 1\n}\\right\]$
%[text] Now that we're able to draw random frames and locate their relations, we'd be able to acquire how to move around the frame and to attach a robotics model onto the different frames, then later use d-h parameters...
%[text] #### Ex 2.3 Using frame transform to find the end effector (EOF) position and orientation representation
%[text] given a EOF position, orientation with it's SE3 object, in a random form peof = round(10\*rand(3,1)'), rotm\_eof
% Define three frame locations, the world frame, end effector frame - (designed to be) based
% on the frame of {B}, then the definition for the frame {B}, at the base
% origin of frame {B} and the actual frame {B} orientation.

% Note that all the rotation matrix (rotm), and the translation vector
% (trvec) are all defined as in world frame.

worldFrame = se3 % eye(4) %[output:793ff139]
eofFrame_World = se3(quat2rotm(randrot),round(10*rand(3,1)')) % end effector frame based on world frame %[output:5ac51b8d]
frameB = se3(eul2rotm([0 pi 0]),round(eofFrame_World.trvec*.8)) % frame b orientation and b_original %[output:8ca49cc4]

figure %[output:1e29e312]
axes( 'DataAspectRatio', [1 1 1], 'View', [37.5 30] ) %[output:1e29e312]
plotframe(worldFrame.rotm, worldFrame.trvec) %[output:1e29e312]
xlabel( 'X' ), ylabel( 'Y' ), zlabel( 'Z' ) %[output:1e29e312]
axis padded %[output:1e29e312]
hold on %[output:1e29e312]

plotframe(frameB.rotm, frameB.trvec) %[output:1e29e312]
plotframe(eofFrame_World.rotm, eofFrame_World.trvec) %[output:1e29e312]
plotline(worldFrame.trvec, frameB.trvec) %[output:1e29e312]
%[text] In defining and simulation, almost all the actual object, has to be declared in the "world" frame, and in the individual numbering, as like $^A\_B R$, $^B\_C R$, or $^A p\_{1}$, $^Bp\_{Aorg}$, all the vectors and matrix are either 3 by 1 and 3 by three, and on appearance its just numbers. One has to be sure how all the referred base frame is rotated and located!!!
% using all the different "world" based se3 object (orientation +
% position), finding the eof "Transformation" object based on frame {B}
%[text] !!! Both homogeneous transformation operator ($^A\_B T$) and frames = rotation matrix (orientation) + translation vector (position) !!!! can both be used as the se3 object!!! 
% excercise of using object utilites as a frame (orientation + position)
dist(eofFrame_World,frameB)     % find the eucleadean distance between end effector to the frame b base %[output:00c47dad]
interp(frameB,eofFrame_World,3) % interpolate points between two "point of orientation" %[output:09896a4e]
%[text] Using the same se3 object as a standard Homogenous Transform 
rotm(eofFrame_World) %[output:2df9499d]
eofFrame_World * frameB         % multiplication of two "point + orientation" i.e. ^A_B T * ^B_C T  %[output:24aeff0c]
frameB %[output:3ce0bf95] %[output:8e078bb0]
